7:05 PM
Good — that reframes everything. This stops being "ship a War simulator" and becomes "use War as the vehicle to learn Go fundamentals + Git workflow." The game is simple enough that nothing hides behind it, but rich enough to hit the concepts that matter.

Let me lay out the learning architecture before we write code.

What War actually teaches you in Go
War is well-chosen because it forces you through the core language surface without algorithmic distraction:

Structs and methods — Card, Deck, Player are your first encounter with Go's "no classes, just structs + methods" model. This is the biggest mental shift coming from Python/TS.
Value vs pointer receivers — Card is a value (small, immutable, copy it freely). Player needs a pointer receiver because Draw() mutates the hand. Getting this wrong is the #1 Go beginner bug, and War makes the consequence visible: draw from a value receiver and the card never leaves the hand.
Slices as the foundational collection — Go has no built-in queue. You build one from a slice. Reslicing (hand[1:]), append semantics, and the sharp edge of shared backing arrays all show up naturally.
Enums via iota — Suit teaches Go's idiom for what TS would do with a union type.
Interfaces — deferred until you need them (fmt.Stringer for printing cards is the gentle first one).
Error handling — Draw() on an empty hand: do you panic, return (Card, error), or guard with HasCards()? Real design conversation.
Testing — Go's table-driven test style is a genuinely different muscle than pytest/vitest.
How I'd sequence this as a course
Each concept gets its own branch, its own PR, its own review. That is the Git curriculum — you're not learning Git separately, you're learning it by shipping War one slice at a time.

Phase	Go concept	Git concept
0	go mod init, hello world	repo init, .gitignore, first commit, remote
1	Card struct, iota, Stringer	feature branch → PR → review → merge
2	Deck, slices, shuffle	branch protection, required PR before merge
3	Player, pointer vs value receivers	meaningful commit messages, atomic commits
4	game loop, the war edge case	rebase vs merge, keeping history clean
5	table-driven tests, seeded RNG	required status checks (CI must pass to merge)
6	Stats, interfaces, refactor	tags / releases, v0.1.0
This maps cleanly onto your "do it once, automate it, track it" instinct — by phase 5 the GitHub Actions workflow runs go test on every PR, and branch protection won't let you merge red. That's the automation payoff baked into the learning.

