7:07 PM
Perfect. Zero Go, GitHub, and you want the complete mental model in plain English before a single line of code exists. That's exactly right — and it's especially right for Go, because Go punishes you for carrying Python/TS habits in. We spend this whole response building the blueprint. No .go files yet.

One thing I need to correct up front, because it shapes everything below:

Go has no classes. Drop the word.
You wrote "cards → class." In Python or TS that's correct. In Go there is no class keyword, no inheritance, no constructors-as-special-methods. This isn't Go being limited — it's a deliberate design choice that will make your code cleaner once it clicks. Here's the replacement model:

A struct is just a bundle of named fields. Card holds a rank and a suit. That's the data, and only the data.
A method is a normal function with a small label saying "this attaches to Card." The behavior lives next to the data but isn't trapped inside it.
A constructor is just a plain function you write by convention, named NewDeck(), that returns a built struct. Nothing magic.
So everywhere your instinct says "class," translate to "struct + the methods attached to it." Same intuition, different machinery. By the end of this project that translation will be automatic, and you'll see why Go people argue it's less code for more clarity — there's no class ceremony, no self, no __init__, no inheritance tree to reason about.

The whole game in plain English
Let me describe every moving part as a concept first. We'll name four things. Three are nouns (data) and one is the verb (the loop that runs everything).

1. The Card
A card is the smallest, dumbest thing in the system. It knows two facts about itself and does nothing:

its rank — how strong it is (a 2 is weakest, an Ace is strongest)
its suit — spades, clubs, hearts, or diamonds
The critical insight for War specifically: suit never decides anything. In poker, suit matters. In War, two cards of equal rank tie regardless of suit — and a tie triggers a "war." So suit exists only so we can print "Ace of Spades" and have it feel like a real card. Rank is the only thing we ever compare.

We'll represent rank as a plain number so comparison is trivial — a bigger number beats a smaller number, full stop. Jack/Queen/King/Ace are just the numbers 11/12/13/14 wearing fancy names when we print them. This is a deliberate design move: store the thing that makes comparison easy, translate to pretty names only at the moment of display. That single decision deletes a whole category of comparison bugs.

A card never changes after it's made. Once it's the Ace of Spades, it's the Ace of Spades forever. That property — "immutable, small, copy it freely" — is why, when we get to Go specifics, a Card will be a value you copy rather than something you point at. Hold that thought; it pays off later.

2. The Deck
The deck is a container with three jobs and no opinions about the game:

Build itself — produce all 52 unique cards: every one of the 13 ranks paired with every one of the 4 suits. Four suits times thirteen ranks is fifty-two. We generate them with two nested loops, not by typing out 52 lines.
Shuffle — scramble its own order randomly.
Deal — split itself cleanly in half, 26 cards to each player.
Notice the deck does not know how to play War. It doesn't compare cards, doesn't track score, doesn't know players take turns. It only knows how to be a well-formed, shuffled, splittable stack of cards. Each piece knows only its own job. That separation is the single most important habit this project is teaching you, and it's what "best practices / write less code" actually means in practice — not clever lines, but each part having exactly one responsibility so nothing tangles.

One subtle thing about shuffling we'll handle deliberately: randomness in a learning/testing project should be controllable. We'll feed the shuffler a "seed" — a starting number. Same seed in, same shuffle out, every time. That sounds like it defeats the point of shuffling, but it's the thing that lets us write a test that says "deal this exact game and assert the outcome." Real randomness for play, reproducible randomness for tests. We design that in from the start rather than bolting it on.

3. The Player
A player is a name plus a hand of cards held in a specific order that matters. The hand is the concept where Go is going to teach you the most, so I want to slow down here.

Think of the hand as a line of people waiting — a queue. Two operations, two ends:

You draw from the top (the front of the line) — that's the card you play this round.
When you win cards, they go to the bottom (the back of the line).
Top and bottom are different ends on purpose. This ordering is the actual engine of War — it's why games end. Cards you win cycle to the back and won't come up again until you've played through everything ahead of them. Without the two-ends rule, the game's rhythm breaks.

Go gives you no ready-made "queue" type. You build one out of a slice (Go's resizable list). "Draw from the top" becomes "take the first element and keep the rest." "Win to the bottom" becomes "append to the end." Plain English first; the slice mechanics will feel obvious once the concept is locked, instead of you fighting syntax and concept simultaneously.

A player can also answer one question about itself: "do I still have cards?" When the answer is no, that player has lost. That's the whole win condition.

4. The Game — the verb
The first three things are nouns that sit there. The Game is the loop that makes them interact. It holds the two players and runs rounds until someone's out of cards. One round, in plain English:

Each player draws their top card. Put both cards on the table (the "pot").
Compare ranks.
Higher rank wins — that player takes both table cards to the bottom of their hand.
Equal rank → WAR.
War resolution (this is the one genuinely tricky rule, so here it is slowly):
The tie stays on the table.
Each player lays 3 cards face-down onto the pot (the stakes), then 1 card face-up.
Compare the two new face-up cards.
Higher one wins the entire pot — the original tie, all the face-down stakes, everything.
If those face-up cards also tie? War again, recursively, stacking more cards onto the same pot until someone wins.
The edge case that separates a toy from a correct program: what if a player doesn't have enough cards to fund a war — they need to lay down 4 but only have 2? That player simply loses the game. We must handle "ran out of cards mid-war," not just "ran out of cards at the start of a round." Forgetting this is the most common way a War implementation is subtly broken, and writing the test that catches it is part of the curriculum.
Termination guarantee: real War between evenly matched players can loop nearly forever. A correct simulation needs a stop condition — a maximum round count — after which we declare the winner by who holds more cards. We design the loop knowing it must be guaranteed to end.
Read those five steps back and notice: everything is described without any code, and yet it's precise enough to test against. That's the standard we're holding. If you can't say in English exactly what a round does — including the war-with-not-enough-cards case — we don't write the function yet.

The Go concepts each piece will force you to meet
So you can see the learning shape, not just the game shape — here's what each noun drags in, in the order we'll hit it:

The Card introduces structs (data bundles), iota (Go's clean way to make the four suits), and your first interface — Stringer, which is just Go's agreed-upon way of saying "here's how I print myself." Gentle, concrete, no abstraction for its own sake.

The Deck introduces slices for real — building 52 cards with nested loops, and the seeded-randomness design we discussed.

The Player introduces the concept that will bite everyone once and then never again: value vs. pointer. When a method needs to change the thing it's attached to — like Draw() permanently removing a card from the hand — it must operate on the real player, not a throwaway copy. A Card never changes, so it's copied freely (a value). A Player's hand changes constantly, so methods touch the original (a pointer). We'll make this concrete and visible — I'll show you the exact bug where a card refuses to leave the hand — rather than stating it as a rule to memorize. This one distinction is most of what makes Go feel foreign at first, and War demonstrates it perfectly.

The Game introduces nothing new about the language and everything about composition — how small correct pieces assemble into behavior. By the time you write it, every part it touches is already understood, so the loop reads like the English above.

The Git curriculum, mapped on top
Since each concept is self-contained, each becomes one branch, one pull request, one review, one merge. You learn Git by shipping War one piece at a time — the workflow isn't a separate lesson, it's the delivery mechanism for every phase.

The arc, roughly: Phase 0 is repo setup — git init, a .gitignore so we never commit junk, first commit, push to GitHub. Then each phase that follows is a feature branch → pull request → you review your own diff → merge. Early on we turn on branch protection so main can't be pushed to directly — everything must go through a PR, which forces the good habit before bad ones form. By the testing phase we add a GitHub Action that runs go test automatically on every PR, and a required status check so a red build physically cannot merge. That's your "track it and automate it" philosophy showing up as muscle memory: by the end, broken code can't reach main without you having to remember anything.

That's the complete blueprint — every aspect of the game in natural language, every Go concept named and placed, the Git workflow layered on, and zero code written. Before we touch a keyboard, the test is: does the round logic, including the war-with-insufficient-cards edge case, feel completely clear when you read it back?

If yes, the natural first step is Phase 0 — setting up the repo, .gitignore, and the GitHub side properly so the workflow is in place before any Go exists. If any part of the round/war flow is still fuzzy, we stay in plain English and nail it first. Which way do you want to go?

